[49m[38;5;10m+     975[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     976[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     977[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     978[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     979[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Bedrock (Agents, Knowledge Bases, Guardrails, foundation model with strong instruction-following and tool-use, embedding model), Amazon OpenSearch Serverless, AWS HealthLake (where authenticated patients have institutional EHR relationship), AWS Lambda, AWS Step Functions, Amazon API Gateway, AWS WAF, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, AWS KMS (with separate keys for the IRB-approved corpus and the recruitment-decision-record store), AWS Secrets Manager, Amazon CloudWatch, AWS CloudTrail, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, Amazon Pinpoint (outbound recruitment-channel messaging), Amazon Connect (warm-handoff to research coordinators), Amazon QuickSight (recruitment-funnel and diversity-action-plan dashboards), Amazon Comprehend Medical (medical NER over patient-reported text). Optionally: Amazon SageMaker (custom vulnerability-flag classifier hosting). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     980[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **External Inputs** | IRB-approved trial corpus per active trial (protocol summary, recruitment FAQ, visit-schedule summary, study-procedure summary, disclosures, disqualified-participant communication, coordinator-handoff language) authored in IRB-approved language, reviewed by IRB, and version-controlled. Eligibility-criteria encoding per trial with named clinical-leadership ownership per criterion, deterministic evaluation logic where applicable, patient-facing question phrasing reviewed by IRB, and verification-source designation. Per-trial trial-state feed from the institution's clinical-trial management system, sponsor-recruitment-tracking systems, and ClinicalTrials.gov listing data. Per-trial diversity-action-plan with stratum-level recruitment targets where the trial is FDA-regulated. Multilingual translations of all IRB-approved content reviewed by clinical leadership and IRB. Coordinator team workflow integration with per-trial coordinator-queue routing. Institutional research-recruitment landing page or sponsor-recruitment landing page or institutional patient-app integration. Identity-and-consent infrastructure with research-data-handling-per-IRB-approved-plan posture. <!-- TODO: verify; specific external inputs vary by institution and per trial; the per-trial IRB-approved corpus and per-trial eligibility-criteria encoding are the largest per-trial setup costs --> |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     981[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Per-Lambda least-privilege roles. The trial-corpus retrieval Lambdas have read access to per-trial Knowledge Base namespaces. The eligibility-evaluator Lambdas have read access to per-trial criterion-rule store. The prescreen-store Lambda has write access to the prescreen store. The coordinator-handoff Lambda has write access to the per-trial coordinator-queue and to the Connect queue. The chart-context Lambda has read access to HealthLake (where the patient has institutional EHR relationship and consent permits). The amendment-driven re-presentation workflow has write access to the trial-corpus store. None of the assistant's Lambdas have write access to the clinical record except for institutionally-approved recruitment-event records (e.g., FHIR Communication resources for the conversation log, where the institution permits assistant-originated records, with explicit patient consent and IRB-approved provisions). Resource-based policies pin invoking principals to the production agent and API Gateway stage ARNs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     982[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA and Compliance** | AWS BAA signed. Verify all services in scope are HIPAA-eligible at build time. The assistant is patient-facing recruitment software for research, with IRB-approved-content-only output discipline, eligibility-evaluation behavior, and coordinator-handoff orchestration. Legal counsel familiar with HIPAA, 45 CFR 46 (Common Rule), 21 CFR Parts 50 and 56 (FDA-regulated research), 21 CFR Part 11 (electronic records and electronic signatures where applicable), 45 CFR 164.512(i) (HIPAA's research provisions), state-specific medical-record statutes, state-specific research-consent laws where applicable, ICH E6 Good Clinical Practice guidelines, the FDA's 2022 draft guidance on diversity action plans, and (where the trial is FDA-regulated) the FDA's IND or IDE record-keeping requirements reviews the data-handling posture. The IRB reviews the assistant's recruitment script, prescreen flow, FAQ content, and routing logic. The institutional regulatory team reviews the FDA-strategy positioning. The trial sponsor's regulatory team is involved for sponsor-funded trials. International trial sites bring regional regulatory frameworks (EU CTR, MHRA in the UK, PMDA in Japan, NMPA in China). <!-- TODO: verify; clinical-trial-recruitment regulatory landscape includes 45 CFR 46, 21 CFR Parts 50 and 56, ICH E6 GCP, FDA SaMD where applicable, FDA's diversity-action-plan guidance and FDORA legislation, regional regulatory frameworks for international trials, state-specific research-consent and medical-record statutes --> |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     983[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | IRB-approved corpus, recruitment-conversation archive, recruitment-decision-record journal, prescreen store: SSE-KMS with customer-managed keys. IRB-approved corpus: separately-managed customer key for blast-radius containment and for IRB-aligned access-control discipline. Recruitment-decision-record journal: separately-managed customer key. S3 archives: Object Lock in compliance mode for the retention window (sized to the longer of HIPAA's six-year minimum, IRB-approved retention plan, FDA IND or IDE retention, and any sponsor or institutional retention requirements). DynamoDB tables: customer-managed KMS at rest, with sensitive tables (IRB-approved corpus, eligibility-criterion store, recruitment-decision-record journal) on separate keys. Lambda environment variables: KMS-encrypted. Secrets Manager: customer-managed KMS. TLS in transit for all AWS API calls and all integrations with external systems. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     984[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: tool Lambdas that call EHRs, the institution's CTMS, sponsor-recruitment systems, the IRB review-tracking system, and coordinator workflow systems run in VPC with controlled egress. PrivateLink to vendor-hosted endpoints where supported; tightly-scoped NAT path with allow-list otherwise. VPC endpoints for DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch Logs, EventBridge, Bedrock, OpenSearch Serverless, HealthLake, Step Functions, Pinpoint, Connect, Comprehend Medical, and SageMaker (where used). The patient-facing edge is public; the back-office and trial-management traffic is private. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     985[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled with data events on all sensitive S3 buckets (audit-archive, recruitment-decision-record-journal, IRB-approved-corpus archive, recruitment-funnel data) and DynamoDB tables (trial-corpus, trial-state, eligibility-criterion, recruitment-cohort, prescreen, coordinator-handoff-queue, recruitment-decision-record, consent record), Secrets Manager secrets, and customer-managed KMS keys. Bedrock and Bedrock Agents invocations logged. Lambda invocations logged. API Gateway access logs enabled. Step Functions execution logs enabled. Connect interactions logged with appropriate retention. Pinpoint message-status logs preserved. CloudTrail logs in a dedicated S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode. Audit retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, IRB-approved retention plan, FDA IND or IDE retention obligations, sponsor or institutional research-data-retention requirements, and litigation-hold obligations. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     986[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic prospective-participant profiles stratified by therapeutic area, by eligibility complexity, by demographic stratum (per the trial's diversity-action-plan), by referral source, by language, by health-literacy level, by age cohort, by social-determinant flags, by vulnerability indicators. Synthetic IRB-approved trial corpora across multiple therapeutic areas with realistic protocol-summary, FAQ, visit-schedule, study-procedure, and disclosure content. Synthetic eligibility-criterion encodings across simple-structured, complex-structured, and clinical-judgment categories with realistic per-criterion logic. Synthetic conversation histories covering trial introduction, FAQ-question handling, prescreen completion, eligibility-determination scenarios (clearly-disqualified, uncertain-pending, clearly-eligible-pending), coordinator-handoff scheduling, escalation scenarios, and vulnerability-flag scenarios. Test CTMS, sponsor-recruitment systems, ClinicalTrials.gov listing feeds, and IRB review-tracking systems with synthetic trials. Test trial-amendment scenarios with re-presentation workflows. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     987[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | At a large academic medical center or institutional research-recruitment platform scale (50-200 active trials with per-trial recruitment campaigns; 1,000-10,000 prospective-participant conversations per month across the trial portfolio; average 6-15 turns per conversation; average 3,000 tokens of prompt and 600 tokens of response per turn for the orchestration model plus tool-call overhead; plus per-trial corpus management, per-trial state tracking, eligibility evaluation, coordinator-handoff orchestration, and per-trial recruitment-funnel reporting): Bedrock LLM invocations typically $40,000-200,000 per month for a Sonnet-class orchestration model, totaling approximately $480,000-2.4M per year. Bedrock Agents and Knowledge Bases hosting plus the OpenSearch Serverless retrieval indices typically $60,000-200,000 per year. Lambda, API Gateway, WAF, DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch, CloudTrail, EventBridge, Kinesis Firehose, Glue, Athena, Step Functions total approximately $80,000-300,000 per year combined. AWS HealthLake (where used) typically $20,000-150,000 per year (varies with FHIR-resource volume and population size). Pinpoint typically $20,000-100,000 per year. Connect typically $40,000-200,000 per year. Comprehend Medical typically $10,000-60,000 per year. SageMaker (when used) typically $10,000-40,000 per year. Total AWS infrastructure typically $720,000-3.5M per year at this scale. The coordinator team workforce cost (employed or contracted research coordinators) is typically larger than the AWS infrastructure cost and is the dominant operational expense. The per-trial setup cost (IRB-approved content authoring, eligibility-criterion encoding, FAQ population, coordinator-team training, IRB review and amendment cycles) is a substantial per-trial investment in clinical and regulatory time. <!-- TODO: replace with verified pricing once the implementing team validates against the AWS Pricing Calculator; specific costs depend on Bedrock model choice, conversation volume across the trial portfolio, per-trial setup throughput, and channel mix --> |
