[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1687[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1688[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A typical performance profile across a portfolio of trials at a mid-sized academic medical center:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1689[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1690[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Range | Notes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1691[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|-------|-------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1692[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-conversation cost (LLM + infra) | $1.50-$5.00 | Varies with conversation length and trial complexity |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1693[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Conversation completion rate | 55-80% | Patients who enter and complete the prescreen |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1694[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Prescreen completion rate among completers | 75-90% | Patients who finish the prescreen vs. those who drop |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1695[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Handoff acceptance rate (coordinator-side) | 80-95% | Coordinators accept the handoff package as actionable |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1696[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Coordinator time saved per handoff | 25-40 minutes | Compared to prescreen-from-scratch by coordinator |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1697[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Citation-coverage rate | 99-100% | Trial-specific assertions with valid IRB-approved citation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1698[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Novel-language detection rate | <0.5% | Output-safety detections per turn |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1699[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Recommendation-pattern detection rate | <0.3% | Output-safety detections per turn |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1700[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort prescreen-yield disparity | <2x | Ratio of best to worst stratum, target |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1701[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Time to coordinator follow-up | 1-3 business days | From handoff scheduled to coordinator contact |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1702[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1703[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO: verify; specific performance ranges depend on trial mix, population, channel distribution, model choice, and corpus quality; replace with measured values once a deployment has real data -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1704[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1705[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Where the recipe struggles:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1706[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1707[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Trials with extremely complex eligibility criteria.** Trials with dozens of criteria including multiple lab-window-and-reading-pair requirements, sequential treatment-history-and-response criteria, or detailed prior-authorization-style insurance criteria stress the prescreen format. The conversation can become a survey rather than a conversation, and patients drop out.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1708[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Trials with low patient self-report fidelity.** Patients reporting medication names, lab values, and treatment timelines often do not have the information at hand. The prescreen captures patient-reported information with explicit caveats, but the coordinator still has to verify, which limits the time savings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1709[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Sponsor-recruitment channels with mixed-quality patient pools.** Sponsor-funded recruitment campaigns that drive high volumes of low-quality prospective participants overwhelm the prescreen even when the assistant scales well. The platform's value is highest when paired with disciplined upstream channel selection.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1710[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Trials with rapidly-changing eligibility.** Trials in active competitive enrollment with frequent IRB amendments stress the amendment-driven re-presentation workflow. Patients in flight at the moment of an amendment may need re-presentation more than once.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1711[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Underrepresented-population reach.** The platform is a force multiplier for patients already plugged into the digital channels through which it operates. Reaching patients in the populations the trial's diversity-action-plan targets requires deliberate channel diversification, partnerships with community-based organizations, and per-cohort monitoring with corrective action.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1712[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Pediatric and surrogate-decision-maker scenarios.** The architecture supports them, but each variant brings additional identity, consent, and assent considerations that meaningfully change the conversation flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1713[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Multi-trial scenarios.** Where a patient is potentially eligible for multiple trials, the assistant has to handle the multi-trial scenario carefully, and the institutional policy on cross-trial communication varies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1714[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Decentralized trials.** The recruitment-platform reach extends well beyond academic-medical-center catchment areas, but the visit-schedule-and-procedure language has to be tailored to the decentralized design, and the coordinator-handoff workflow looks different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1715[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1716[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
